name: La Cantina de San Angel
selection: Tacos (beef, chicken, fried fish), empanadas, salads, chicken with Mexican rice, guacamole, churros, and margaritas
setting_atmosphere:
A popular spot for a quick meal, with 150 covered outdoor seats.
When it’s extra busy, the back of La Hacienda de San Angel’s dining room
is opened for air-conditioned seating.
summary:
Tacos with seasoned beef, chicken, or fried fish; fried cheese empanada;
grilled chicken with Mexican rice, corn, cascabel sauce, and pickled
onions; guacamole and chips; churros; margaritas. For kids, chicken tacos,
empanadas, chicken tenders, or mac and cheese.
plan_name: Dine at La Cantina de San Angel

name: Connections Café
summary: Starbucks coffee and snacks near the Creations Shop in EPCOT.

name: Connections Eatery
selection: Burgers, pizza, salads
summary: Fast-casual service eatery in World Discovery, near Guardians of the Galaxy Cosmic Rewind. Burgers and pizza are prepared in a show kitchen.

name: Crêpes à Emporter
summary: Food window to get crêpes and drinks outside La Crêperie de Paris, near Remy's Ratatouille Adventure.

name: Les Halles Boulangerie-Patisserie
selection: Salads, sandwiches (ham and cheese, Brie, cranberry, and apple), cheese plates, quiches, soups, delicate pastries
summary:
Les Halles is the highest-rated counter-service restaurant in EPCOT
and one of the best in the World. Breads and pastries are made on-site. For
an authentic Parisian experience, grab a half-baguette (ask for extra butter)
and eat it while you walk around France. Usually crowded all day.
house_specialties:
The beautiful deli–bakery case is stocked with goodies such as
sandwiches (ham and cheese; Brie, cranberry, and apple), importedcheese
plates, quiches, soups, and delicate pastries.
plan_name: Dine at Les Halles Boulangerie & Pâtisserie

name: Katsura Grill
selection: Sushi, udon noodle bowls, teriyaki bowls, chicken or beef curry, green-tea cheesecake. Beer, sake, and plum wine.
setting_atmosphere: Sounds of the babbling waterfall and koi pond gently welcome guests as they approach the outdoor dining area. There are clusters of tables and chairs, some near the small waterfall, and some across the bridge under the shade of beautiful, blossoming trees. Generally there is plenty of shade in either area. Views of the garden, the Japan pavilion, and the World Showcase promenade and lagoon can be enjoyed here.
summary: Possibly the loveliest spot to escape the Epcot crowd and have a quick meal outside.

name: Kringla Bakeri og Kafe
selection: Norwegian pastries/cakes, rice cream, sandwiches, lattes and imported beers and wines
summary:
Limited menu and hours. The School Bread (a sweet roll filled with
custard and dipped in coconut) is popular. Shaded outdoor seating.
house_specialties:
Norwegian pastries and desserts, iced coffee, and imported beers
and wines.
plan_name: Dine at Kringla Bakeri og Kafe

name: Lotus Blossom Café
selection: Egg rolls, pot stickers, curry, sesame chicken salad, fried rice, orange chicken, soup,  lychee ice cream, plum wine
summary: The menu rarely changes, and the food remains a snooze.
house_specialties:
Pork and vegetable egg rolls, pot stickers, orange chicken, chicken
fried rice, caramel-ginger or lychee ice cream, plum
wine.

name: The Odyssey
selection: Occasionally offers wine, beer, cocktails, and snacks
summary: A former restaurant and more recent festival center, The Odyssey is a classic EPCOT building that is serving as Quick Service dining during the long-term remodel of the park.

name: Refreshment Outpost
selection: Hot dogs, soft-serve in a waffle cone, slushes, coffee or tea, draft Safari Amber beer
summary:
The hot dogs here aren’t bad at all, but there are plenty of better
dining options within a few minutes’ walk.
house_specialties:
All-beef hot dogs, slushies, sodas, draft Safari Amber and other
beers.

name: Refreshment Port
selection: Changes frequently. Currently poutine, lobster chips, ice cream, and some inventive cocktails.
summary:
From croissant doughnuts to pork-belly Bloody Marys, you never
know what you’ll find here—but chances are that it will be good.
house_specialties: Poutine, chicken nuggets, unusual alcoholic drinks and beer.
location_details: Between Canada and World Showcase Plaza

name: Regal Eagle Smokehouse: Craft Drafts & Barbecue
selection: Barbecue and beer
setting_atmosphere: An enclosed, colonial-style patio serves as the main dining area here, with outdoor seating around a show-kitchen smoker when the weather is nice.  Rolls of paper towels are set on every table, as required by barbecue law.
summary:
Regal Eagle
serves passable barbecue in hearty portions, with the Texas brisket (on
garlic toast) being our favorite. If you’re craving more, The Polite Pig at
Disney Springs sets the standard in Walt Disney World.
house_specialties:
Regional barbecue meat specialties, including Memphis smoked ribs,
Kansas City chicken, North Carolina chopped pork, and Texas brisket, plus burgers,
salads, and vegetarian options. Usually serves at least four different beers
from around the country, plus hard ciders, wines, and specialty cocktails.
plan_name: Dine at Regal Eagle Smokehouse: Craft Drafts & Barbecue
sort_name: regal eagle smokehouse craft drafts barbecue

name: Sommerfest
selection: Bratwurst, frankfurter, sauerkraut, nudelgratin, cold potato salad, apple strudel, Black Forest cake, German wine, beer
summary:
Tables are set up in the courtyard. Much of the food looks better
than it tastes.
house_specialties: Bratwurst, jumbo pretzel, cold beer.

name: Sunshine Seasons
selection: Rotisserie chicken, pork chop, veggie flatbread, fish tacos, and turkey on ciabatta, noodle dishes, soup, salad
summary:
A place for a quick meal, with enough variety
for everyone in the family.
house_specialties:
Sunshine Seasons is set up like a food court you would find in one of Disney's moderate resorts. During lunch up to three different stations serve hot meals, usually wood-fired grills and rotisseries, with
rotisserie chicken and wood-grilled fish with seasonal vegetables; (2)
sandwiches; and (3)soup-and-salad. During slower times of the day there's grab-and-go food.
plan_name: Dine at Sunshine Seasons Food Fair

name: Tangierine Café: Flavors of the Medina
selection: Grilled kebabs, falafel pita
setting_atmosphere: The indoor area resembles a very small cafeteria, but the outdoor seating is in a quaint, shaded area that has a view of the promenade and is great for people watching.
summary: Once one of the highest-rated quick-service restaurants, Tangierine Cafe will be largely unrecognizable compared with its pre-pandemic form. The location, operating still under the Tangierine Cafe name, is now a festival booth serving a limited selection of foods according to the festival theme. Think kebabs, bread, and some sort of dessert with limited drink selections. Lines are rarely long, and the food is good but often overlooked during the perpetual EPCOT festival seasons.
sort_name: tangierine caf flavors of the medina

name: Yorkshire County Fish Shop
selection: Fish and chips, Victoria sponge cake, Bass Pale Ale draft, and Harp Lager
summary:
There’s usually a line for the crisp, hot fish-and-chips at this convenient
fast-food window attached to the Rose & Crown Dining Room. A tasty chicken-and-mushroom pie might
be served during cooler months. Outdoor seating overlooks the lagoon.
house_specialties: Fish-and-chips, Bass Pale Ale draft, and Harp Lager.
plan_name: Dine at Yorkshire County Fish Shop

name: Akershus Royal Banquet Hall
entree_range: Breakfast: Adult $53, Child $34. Lunch: Adult $63, Child $41. Dinner: Adult $63, Child $41
selection: Koldtbord (meats, cheeses, seafood, and salads), roasted chicken, salmon, goat cheese ravioli, eef-and-pork dumplings
setting_atmosphere:
The inside of Akershus looks like every child’s
vision of a fairy-tale castle: high ceilings, stone archways, sumptuous purple
carpets, regal banners flying. What’s mildly surprising, given the attention
to authenticity elsewhere in EPCOT, is that it doesn’t look more like
the real Akershus Castle in Oslo, which has plain wooden floors; flat, simple ceilings; and painted brick arches. Disney’s version is almost as ungodly
expensive as the real thing, though, and you’re apt to hear norsk spoken
by your servers. Close enough for us. The saving grace is that most visitors
don’t realize that it is in fact a restaurant and walk right by.
other_recommendations: Beer on tap, wine, aquavit cocktails.
summary:
Akershus has never been on our “you’ve just
gotta try this” list, but if you have kids who love the Disney princesses, they
won’t be disappointed. There was a time when the Scandinavian-style buffet
was noteworthy, but these days all of the attention in the kitchen goes to feeding
families fast. As for the prices? You’re paying for that princess face time.
plan_name: Dine at Akershus Royal Banquet Hall

name: Biergarten Restaurant
entree_range: Lunch: Adult $49, Child $27 ◆ Dinner: Adult $49, Child $27
selection: German roasted meats, various salads (potato, beet, and lettuce), desserts
setting_atmosphere:
Biergarten is a hefty German restaurant set
inside a nighttime Teutonic town square. You’re seated at long tables lined
up in rows emanating like the moon’s rays from a central dance floor and
stage. A lederhosen-clad oompah band plays and encourages diners to
sing along. Tables are not shared between families, and there’s plenty of
space between occupied tables.
summary: The buffet is stacked with an astonishing amount of food of good quality. There are plenty of places in Walt Disney World where you could pay more for less. If you leave here hungry, ask your doctor about tapeworms. The lively 25-minute show (one every hour) and noisy dining room are part of the fun, especially for families. And kids seem to love the place.
house_specialties:
Potato salad, traditional German sausages, and homemade
spaetzle.

name: Le Cellier Steakhouse
selection: Steak, soup, dumplings, mac and cheese and other steakhouse sides, poutine fries
setting_atmosphere: Walk past the Canada Pavilion’s pretty gardens into this small, darkened dining room, intended to evoke the look and feel of a wine cellar. Given the escalated prices, it doesn’t feel upscale, with heavy wooden tables and no linens, but the crowd doesn’t seem to mind— the steaks make up for the ambience. Service is “cheerful Canadian,” meaning servers will apologize to you if you spill something on them.
other_recommendations:
For sides, share the five-cheese mac-and-cheese,
the loaded mashed potatoes, or the poutine. For dessert, the warm pecan–
brown butter tart. Excellent wine selection.
summary:
Le Cellier is expensive, but the steaks are perfectly seasoned
and cooked, with a beautiful char. Service is unrushed—it’s possible
for a full dinner to take 2 hours, so plan accordingly. The menu is the
same at lunch and dinner.
house_specialties: Filet mignon; Canadian Cheddar soup.

name: Chefs de France
selection: Baked goat cheese salad, boeuf bourguignon linguine, creme brulee
setting_atmosphere:
It’s like stepping into a busy bistro. The smells
are delicious, with baguettes from the on-site bakery on every table. White
cloth napkins and padded banquettes accentuate the classic bistro decor of
the main dining room, where window tables make for fun people-watching
on the World Showcase Promenade.
other_recommendations: Ask your server for the vegetarian options.
summary:
The charcuterie
plate isn’t as good as the ones at Via Napoli or Le Cellier. Stick to
the French onion soup and Boeuf Bourguignon.
house_specialties:
Dishes inspired by the three French chefs for whom
the restaurant is named: Paul Bocuse, Gaston Lenôtre, and Roger Vergé. For the classic French experience, try the prix fixe menu with French onion
soup topped with Gruyère for your appetizer.

name: Coral Reef Restaurant
selection: Lobster seafood boil, seared mahi mahi, grilled rib-eye
setting_atmosphere:
Though the decor could use a face-lift, you
can’t beat the view in this darkened dining room, which faces one of the
world’s largest saltwater aquariums; tiered seating gives everyone a pretty
good view of the multitude of fishes (and sometimes Mickey in a scuba
suit). The ethereal entryway gives the impression that you’re going under
the sea; special light fixtures throw ripple patterns on the ceiling.
summary:
Not the best restaurant in EPCOT by a long
shot, but Coral Reef is a great escape from the Florida sun. Grab a souvenir
fish guide and check out the more than 2,000 sea creatures that call this
place home—but that are probably not on the menu.
house_specialties:
Lobster bisque, grilled rib eye.
For kids, grilled fish, steak, chicken, or shrimp.
location_details: inside the Seas Pavilion, to the right of the Seas with Nemo and Friends attraction entrance.

name: La Crêperie de Paris
selection: Crepes and other French favorites
other_recommendations: Note that Crêpes à Emporter offers to-go crêpes and drinks from a window outside this restaurant.
summary: Celebrity chef Jérôme Bocuse offers sweet and savory crêpe options in this new part of the France Pavilion, near Remy's Ratatouille Adventure.

name: Garden Grill Restaurant
entree_range: Breakfast: Adult $42, Child $27 ◆ Lunch: Adult $55, Child $36 ◆ Dinner: Adult $55, Child $36
bar: Wine, beer and some mixed drinks
selection: Grilled beef, turkey breast with stuffing and gravy, and fish of the day. Seasonal cobbler with vanilla whipped cream.
setting_atmosphere:
With the popular Soarin’ Around the World attraction nearby, the all-you-can-eat Garden Grill stays busy, even though the concept and the dining room have grown rather dated. Even so, it’s a classic: The floor revolves slowly as you peer down into the unseen side of scenes from Living with the Land, the Land Pavilion’s ride-through attraction. At about the time you finish a meal, you’ve revolved once, past scenes of a desert, a rainforest, and a farm—an otherwise hidden view of inside the farmhouse. The constant crowing of a “rooster” and dog barks are questionable highlights.

Much more exciting for kids are the Disney characters—Mickey, Chip ’n’ Dale, Pluto, and others make stops along the inner wall of the circular restaurant, far enough away to be safe but close enough for good photos.
other_recommendations: The view, Character dining. Complimentary nonalcoholic beverages included with meals.
summary:
The food quality is, in our estimation, just OK.
Nevertheless, readers really seem to like Garden Grill; we think the retro-
Disney setting and the characters are at least as much of a draw as the
food. If you can’t get an Advance Reservation for one of the other character
meals, this place is worth checking out.
house_specialties:
Grilled beef, chimichurri, turkey breast with stuffing and
gravy, BBQ ribs, mashed potatoes, veggies, and salads made with ingredients
from The Land’s greenhouses. Plant-based options available on request.
plan_name: Dine at The Garden Grill Restaurant

name: La Hacienda de San Angel
selection: Guacamole, queso fundido, pork confit carnitas, taco sampler, short ribs with chimichurri; fried shrimp tacos.
setting_atmosphere:
Right along the waterfront in Mexico, La Hacienda
is a primo spot for watching fireworks through the tall windows. The
interior has authentic touches of Mexico in its lighting and decor.
other_recommendations:
For starters, try the flautas—fried tortillas
with potato, chipotle chicken, cheese, and ranchero sauce. The margaritas
are the real deal—or just go for a flight of fine tequila.
summary:
The menu is simple, but the quality is first rate.
Also, one word: tequila.
house_specialties:
Excellent guacamole; queso fundido; carne asada–style
New York strip; flank steak fajitas with bacon, poblano and bell peppers,
cheese, and salsa; and fried-shrimp tacos with chipotle-lime aioli.
plan_name: Dine at La Hacienda de San Angel

name: Monsieur Paul
parking: Epcot or BoardWalk lot; enter through back gate
selection: Maine lobster with sauteed mushrooms, poached egg, creamy black-truffle bouillon, lamb tenderloin, roasted duck breast
setting_atmosphere: Light and modern, Monsieur Paul is tucked away at the France Pavilion. Access lies up a stairway lined with photos of legendary chef Paul Bocuse, whose son, Jérôme, owns and runs the restaurant, along with Chefs de France. Despite the relaxed ambience, the cuisine is upscale, with sublime sauces and classic preparations. Request a table at the windows to watch the world go by on World Showcase Lagoon. Seats just 120.
summary:
Monsieur Paul may be a bit formal and highpriced
for many park guests, but if you can get past the sticker shock, this
is the spot for a quiet dinner and conversation. Chef Nicolas Lemoyne, who
worked at l’Auberge du Pont de Collonges in Lyon, France, wows diners with
classic French tastes, including warm chocolate-almond cake with raspberry
coulis. There’s also a three-course fixed-price menu,
along with a solid wine list. A rather grown-up kids’ menu includes roasted
salmon and grilled beef tenderloin.

name: Nine Dragons Restaurant
selection: Pork steamed buns, kung pao shrimp, Beijing roast duck salad, five-spiced fish.
setting_atmosphere:
Nine Dragons’ attractive interior—subdued
wood tones, colorful lanterns, beautiful backlit glass sculptures from China—
and efficient service create a respite from the bustle of World Showcase.
Ask for a window seat for a view of passersby on the promenade.
other_recommendations:
Stick to the appetizers and put the chili oil on
everything. It’s made in-house and should be sold as a souvenir.
summary:
You can usually get a table without a wait in
the spacious dining room, and while Nine Dragons gets a bad rep for being
pricey, we think the food and service are above average.

name: Rose & Crown Dining Room
bar: Full bar with Bass, Guinness, and Harp beers on tap.
selection: Fish and chips, Scotch egg, chicken masala, bangers and chips, Guinness, Harp, and Bass beers, as well as other spirits
setting_atmosphere:
Pub in the front, dining room in the back. The
pub hops with activity from open to close and has the look and feel of a
traditional English watering hole: a large, cozy bar with rich wood appointments,
beamed ceilings, and a hardwood floor. The adjoining dining room
is rustic and simple.
summary:
At dinnertime, the Rose & Crown is packed
with folks appropriating tables for the EPCOT fireworks. The food is
good, so branch out and try something new—you can always get fishand-
chips at the adjacent walk-up window, Yorkshire County Fish Shop.
house_specialties:
Fish and chips, bangers and mash (sausage and mashed
potatoes) and shepherd's pie (the vegetarian
version is delicious too), washed down with Bass ale. For dessert try the Sticky Toffee Pudding.
plan_name: Dine at Rose and Crown Dining Room

name: San Angel Inn Restaurante
selection: Corn cakes, quesadillas, queso fresco, chile relleno, carne asada, cheesecake with cajeta
setting_atmosphere:
Step inside the Aztec pyramid in Mexico, navigate
the busy marketplace, and end up at San Angel Inn, which overlooks
a starry sky and the Gran Fiesta Tour boat ride. Its decor is inspired by the
original San Angel Inn in Mexico City and is incredibly atmospheric—it
really does feel like you’re dining in an outdoor Mexican square.
other_recommendations:
Ribeye tacos should please almost anyone.
Try the sweet corn ice cream for dessert.
summary:
The prices may be steep, but the menu goes
beyond the typical tacos and such, offering regional dishes that are difficult
to find in the States. Request a waterside table overlooking the boat
ride for more room and a slightly quieter evening. The dining room is a
cool, quiet respite from the theme park—but you might need a flashlight
to read the menu.

name: Shiki-Sai: Sushi Izakaya
selection: Sushi, grilled items, okonomiyaki
summary: Japanese restaurant that replaced Tokyo Dining on the second level of the Japan Pavilion. It offers shareable sushi and grilled items in the form of small dishes.

name: Space 220 Restaurant
entree_range: Lunch: Adult $55, Child $29 ◆ Dinner: Adult $79, Child $29
selection: Modern American cuisine
setting_atmosphere:
The premise for Space 220 is that you're dining at the Centauri space station, tethered to Florida and flying 220 miles above Epcot. You are seated at tables that look out into space as different astronauts float by on hoverboards or in their space suits.

There are 15 tables in the lounge area, either white or gray, and are in the section next to the bar on the right of the room. The best seats are the 22 window booths, each of which fit 4 people and have spectacular "views". Another 50 tables are spread over the base and upper level of the restaurant.
summary:
Space 220 has the best entrance experience of any Walt Disney World restaurant, and the food is good too. Yes, it's pricey, but to us it's a better value than the Droid Depot at Disney's Hollywood Studios. You'll spend less per person here and you won't feel nearly as rushed.

Space 220 offers fixed-price menus for lunch and dinner. Each includes an appetizer and entree, and for dinner you also get dessert. Several up-charge extras, such as lobster, are also available.

name: Spice Road Table
selection: Lamb sliders with tzatziki, hummus and grape leaves appetizers.
setting_atmosphere:
A prime location for daytime people-watching
and nighttime fireworks, Spice Road Table is situated directly along World
Showcase Lagoon at the front of the Morocco Pavilion. The outdoor covered
patio features excellent dining in plein air when Florida weather cooperates,
and indoor seating provides colorful pops of modern Moroccan decor.
other_recommendations:
Lamb kefta with tzatziki offers a bit of punch
and spice. Spiced shrimp and chicken may sound simple, but the accompanying
sauces and sides elevate the otherwise pedestrian dish to the
next level.
summary: Food quality and service are good here. Appetizers and desserts pair excellently with the restaurant’s extensive wine and cocktail lists. Service is attentive, and the casual atmosphere seems appropriate to the outdoor seating area and modern EPCOT.
house_specialties:
Perfectly fried calamari and hummus fries stand out as
favorites on the small-plates side of the menu.

name: Takumi-Tei
selection: Ponzu crab and toasted crab snacks. Japanese A-5 Wagyu beef tenderloin, roasted duck, sea bass.
setting_atmosphere:
Takumi-Tei's decor celebrates five natural
elements revered by Japanese craftsmen: water, wood, earth, stone, and
washi (paper). The private dining room, home to traditional kaiseki dining,
features a custom waterfall on its feature wall that is designed to
look like it’s flowing straight into the dining table.
other_recommendations:
Sashimi and nigiri with the freshest fish you’ll ever taste; specialty desserts tailor-made for Instagramming, including the clear, perplexingly delicious Japanese water cake.

Read our review of the Chef's Table experience here.
summary:
Filtering classical Japanese cookery through an
upscale modern lens, Takumi-Tei treats diners to an indulgent retreat from
the hustle and bustle of the theme park.
house_specialties:
The menu rotates seasonally to reflect the freshest and
most seasonal produce at the chef’s disposal. The Hama no Kani (“Crab on
the Beach”) appetizer playfully combines two different crab preparations
with frisée, heirloom tomato, and pickled watermelon. A-5 Wagyu beef—the
most prized in the world—anchors the main-course menu, and while it’s a
significant spend, it makes for a meal unlike any other.

name: Teppan Edo
selection: Shrimp tempura roll, salmon, filet mignon, green tea mousse cake
setting_atmosphere:
Six Japanese dining rooms with grills on tables
and entertaining chefs chopping, slicing, and dicing.
summary:
A popular dining option for families, Teppan
Edo was the highest-rated restaurant in Walt Disney World over the past
year. The food quality is comparable to what you’d get in a hometown teppan
place. You’ll get plenty to eat, and the starters include sushi, ribs, edamame,
and miso soup. What’s not to like?
house_specialties:
Chicken, shrimp, beef, scallops, and Asian vegetables
stir-fried on a teppanyaki grill by a knife-juggling chef.

name: Tutto Italia Ristorante
selection: Mozzarella with roasted peppers and basil, pollo e sfilatino, panna cotta, gelato
setting_atmosphere:
Tutto Italia feels like a big restaurant in Rome
or Milan, with murals of a piazza along the wall behind upholstered banquettes.
It can get noisy—if the weather is nice, request an outside table.
other_recommendations: Stick to the least-expensive menu items.
summary:
This should be one of the best Italian restaurants
in Orlando, but it’s not. Everything that happens inside Tutto Italia—
from the cooking to the service—feels like it’s done on autopilot. The food
quality can’t support the prices, even taking the Disney “bubble” cost premium
into account: over $35 for chicken parm is double what you’d pay in
many neighborhood Italian joints and 30% more expensive than in Manhattan.
Everything here needs to be done better.
house_specialties:
It’s hard to identify anything as being done particularly
well.

name: Via Napoli Ristorante e Pizzeria
selection: The best pizza in Walt Disney World
setting_atmosphere:
Three big pizza ovens, named after the three
active Italian volcanoes—Etna, Vesuvio, and Stromboli—are the stars of the
show in this loud, cavernous dining room.
summary:
The Carciofi (artichokes, fontina, and truffle
oil) and four-cheese pies are our favorites.
house_specialties: The best pizza in Walt Disney World.
